==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Thyrsus
<hw>Thyr"sus</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Thyrsi</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/. Cf.
<er>Torso</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A staff entwined with ivy, and
surmounted by a pine cone, or by a bunch of vine or ivy leaves with
grapes or berries. It is an attribute of Bacchus, and of the satyrs and
others engaging in Bacchic rites.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A good to grow on graves⟦br⟧
As twist about a <qex>thyrsus</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs.
Browning.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In my hand I bear⟦br⟧
The <qex>thyrsus</qex>, tipped with fragrant cones of pine.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A species of inflorescence; a
dense panicle, as in the lilac and horse-chestnut.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Thysanopter</ent>⟦br⟧
